word_summaries_chapter_113:
  113:1:1:"The first word of verse (113:1) is an imperative verb (<span class=\"at\">فعل أمر</span>). The verb is second person masculine singular. The verb's triliteral root is <i class=\"ab\">qāf wāw lām</i> (<span class=\"at\">ق و ل</span>)."
  113:1:2:"The second word of verse (113:1) is an imperfect verb (<span class=\"at\">فعل مضارع</span>). The verb is first person singular and is in the indicative mood (<span class=\"at\">مرفوع</span>). The verb's triliteral root is <i class=\"ab\">ʿayn wāw dhāl</i> (<span class=\"at\">ع و ذ</span>)."
  113:1:3:"The third word of verse (113:1) is divided into 2 morphological segments. A preposition and noun. The prefixed preposition <i class=\"ab\">bi</i> is usually translated as \"with\" or \"by\". The noun is masculine and is in the genitive case (<span class=\"at\">مجرور</span>). The noun's triliteral root is <i class=\"ab\">rā bā bā</i> (<span class=\"at\">ر ب ب</span>). Together the segments form a preposition phrase known as <i class=\"ab\">jār wa majrūr</i> (<span class=\"at\">جار ومجرور</span>)."
  113:1:4:"The fourth word of verse (113:1) is a masculine noun and is in the genitive case (<span class=\"at\">مجرور</span>). The noun's triliteral root is <i class=\"ab\">fā lām qāf</i> (<span class=\"at\">ف ل ق</span>)."
  113:2:1:"The first word of verse (113:2) is a preposition."
  113:2:2:"The second word of verse (113:2) is a masculine singular noun and is in the genitive case (<span class=\"at\">مجرور</span>). The noun's triliteral root is <i class=\"ab\">shīn rā rā</i> (<span class=\"at\">ش ر ر</span>)."
  113:2:3:"The third word of verse (113:2) is a relative pronoun."
  113:2:4:"The fourth word of verse (113:2) is a perfect verb (<span class=\"at\">فعل ماض</span>). The verb is third person masculine singular. The verb's triliteral root is <i class=\"ab\">khā lām qāf</i> (<span class=\"at\">خ ل ق</span>)."
  113:3:1:"The first word of verse (113:3) is divided into 2 morphological segments. A conjunction and preposition. The prefixed conjunction <i class=\"ab\">wa</i> is usually translated as \"and\"."
  113:3:2:"The second word of verse (113:3) is a masculine singular noun and is in the genitive case (<span class=\"at\">مجرور</span>). The noun's triliteral root is <i class=\"ab\">shīn rā rā</i> (<span class=\"at\">ش ر ر</span>)."
  113:3:3:"The third word of verse (113:3) is an indefinite masculine active participle and is in the genitive case (<span class=\"at\">مجرور</span>). The active participle's triliteral root is <i class=\"ab\">ghayn sīn qāf</i> (<span class=\"at\">غ س ق</span>)."
  113:3:4:"The fourth word of verse (113:3) is a time adverb."
  113:3:5:"The fifth word of verse (113:3) is a perfect verb (<span class=\"at\">فعل ماض</span>). The verb is third person masculine singular. The verb's triliteral root is <i class=\"ab\">wāw qāf bā</i> (<span class=\"at\">و ق ب</span>)."
  113:4:1:"The first word of verse (113:4) is divided into 2 morphological segments. A conjunction and preposition. The prefixed conjunction <i class=\"ab\">wa</i> is usually translated as \"and\"."
  113:4:2:"The second word of verse (113:4) is a masculine singular noun and is in the genitive case (<span class=\"at\">مجرور</span>). The noun's triliteral root is <i class=\"ab\">shīn rā rā</i> (<span class=\"at\">ش ر ر</span>)."
  113:4:3:"The third word of verse (113:4) is a feminine plural noun and is in the genitive case (<span class=\"at\">مجرور</span>). The noun's triliteral root is <i class=\"ab\">nūn fā thā</i> (<span class=\"at\">ن ف ث</span>)."
  113:4:4:"The fourth word of verse (113:4) is a preposition."
  113:4:5:"The fifth word of verse (113:4) is a masculine plural noun and is in the genitive case (<span class=\"at\">مجرور</span>). The noun's triliteral root is <i class=\"ab\">ʿayn qāf dāl</i> (<span class=\"at\">ع ق د</span>)."
